# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ntfs-filesystem
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] It was developed to overcome scalability, security and other limitations with FAT.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS adds several features that FAT and HPFS lack, including: access control lists (ACLs); filesystem encryption; transparent compression; sparse files; file system journaling and volume shadow copy, a feature that allows backups of a system while in use.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Starting with Windows NT 3.1, it is the default file system of the Windows NT family superseding the File Allocation Table (FAT) file system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS read/write support is available on Linux and BSD using NTFS3 in Linux and NTFS-3G in both Linux and BSD.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS uses several files hidden from the user to store metadata about other files stored on the drive which can help improve speed and performance when reading data.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] In the mid-1980s, Microsoft and IBM formed a joint project to create the next generation of graphical operating system; the result was OS/2 and HPFS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Because Microsoft disagreed with IBM on many important issues, they eventually separated; OS/2 remained an IBM project and Microsoft worked to develop Windows NT and NTFS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The HPFS file system for OS/2 contained several important new features.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] When Microsoft created their new operating system, they borrowed many of these concepts for NTFS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The original NTFS developers were Tom Miller, Gary Kimura, Brian Andrew, and David Goebel.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Probably as a result of this common ancestry, HPFS and NTFS use the same disk partition identification type code (07).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Using the same Partition ID Record Number is highly unusual, since there were dozens of unused code numbers available, and other major file systems have their own codes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] For example, FAT has more than nine (one each for FAT12, FAT16, FAT32, etc.).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Algorithms identifying the file system in a partition type 07 must perform additional checks to distinguish between HPFS and NTFS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The `NTFS.sys` version number (e.g. v5.0 in Windows 2000) is based on the operating system version; it should not be confused with the NTFS version number (v3.1 since Windows XP).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Although subsequent versions of Windows added new file system-related features, they did not change NTFS itself.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] For example, Windows Vista implemented NTFS symbolic links, Transactional NTFS, partition shrinking, and self-healing.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS symbolic links are a new feature in the file system; all the others are new operating system features that make use of NTFS features already in place.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS is optimized for 4 KB clusters, but supports a maximum cluster size of 2 MB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] (Earlier implementations support up to 64 KB) The maximum NTFS volume size that the specification can support is 264 − 1 clusters, but not all implementations achieve this theoretical maximum, as discussed below.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The maximum NTFS volume size implemented in Windows XP Professional is 232 − 1 clusters, partly due to partition table limitations.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] For example, using 64 KB clusters, the maximum size Windows XP NTFS volume is 256 TB minus 64 KB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Using the default cluster size of 4 KB, the maximum NTFS volume size is 16 TB minus 4 KB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Both of these are vastly higher than the 128 GB limit in Windows XP SP1.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The size of a partition in the Master Boot Record (MBR) is limited to 2 TiB with a hard drive with 512-byte physical sectors, although for a 4 KiB physical sector the MBR partition size limit is 16 TiB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] An alternative is to use multiple GUID Partition Table (GPT or "dynamic") volumes for be combined to create a single NTFS volume larger than 2 TiB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Booting from a GPT volume to a Windows environment in a Microsoft supported way requires a system with Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) and 64-bit support.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] GPT data disks are supported on systems with BIOS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] With Windows 10 version 1709 and Windows Server 2019, the maximum *implemented* file size is 8 PB minus 2 MB or 9,007,199,252,643,840 bytes (9 PB).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] While the different NTFS versions are for the most part fully forward- and backward-compatible, there are technical considerations for mounting newer NTFS volumes in older versions of Microsoft Windows.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This affects dual-booting, and external portable hard drives.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] For example, attempting to use an NTFS partition with Windows' feature "Previous Versions" (Volume Shadow Copy) on an operating system that does not support it will result in the contents of those previous versions being lost.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] A Windows command-line utility called convert.exe can convert supporting file systems to NTFS, including HPFS (only on Windows NT 3.1, 3.5, and 3.51), FAT16 and FAT32 (on Windows 2000 and later).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The conversion occurs in-place, meaning the existing files stay where they are and are not re-written during the process.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The process is not reversible without formatting and writing the files again.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] FreeBSD 3.2 released in May 1999 included read-only NTFS support written by Semen Ustimenko.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This implementation was ported to NetBSD by Christos Zoulas and Jaromir Dolecek and released with NetBSD 1.5 in December 2000.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The FreeBSD implementation of NTFS was also ported to OpenBSD by Julien Bordet and offers native read-only NTFS support by default on i386 and amd64 platforms as of version 4.9 released 1 May 2011.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Linux kernel versions 2.1.74 and later include a driver written by Martin von Löwis which has the ability to read NTFS partitions; kernel versions 2.5.11 and later contain a new driver written by Anton Altaparmakov (University of Cambridge) and Richard Russon which supports file read.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The ability to write to files was introduced with kernel version 2.6.15 in 2006 which allows users to write to existing files but does not allow the creation of new ones.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Paragon's NTFS driver (see below) has been merged into kernel version 5.15, and it supports read/write on normal, compressed and sparse files, as well as journal replaying.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS-3G is a free GPL-licensed FUSE implementation of NTFS that was initially developed as a Linux kernel driver by Szabolcs Szakacsits.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] It was re-written as a FUSE program to work on other systems that FUSE supports like macOS, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Solaris, QNX, and Haiku and allows reading and writing to NTFS partitions.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] A performance enhanced commercial version of NTFS-3G, called "Tuxera NTFS for Mac", is also available from the NTFS-3G developers.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Captive NTFS, a 'wrapping' driver that uses Windows' own driver ntfs.sys, exists for Linux.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] It was built as a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) program and released under the GPL but work on Captive NTFS ceased in 2006.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Linux kernel versions 5.15 onwards carry NTFS3, a fully functional NTFS Read-Write driver which works on NTFS versions up to 3.1 and is maintained primarily by the Paragon Software Group.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Mac OS X 10.3 included Ustimenko's read-only implementation of NTFS from FreeBSD.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Then in 2006 Apple hired Anton Altaparmakov to write a new NTFS implementation for Mac OS X 10.6.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Native NTFS write support is included in 10.6 and later, but is not activated by default, although workarounds do exist to enable the functionality.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] However, user reports indicate the functionality is unstable and tends to cause kernel panics.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Paragon Software Group sells a read-write driver named *NTFS for Mac*, which is also included on some models of Seagate hard drives.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The NetDrive package for OS/2 (and derivatives such as eComStation and ArcaOS) supports a plugin which allows read and write access to NTFS volumes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] There is a free-for-personal-use read/write driver for MS-DOS by Avira called "NTFS4DOS".
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Ahead Software developed a "NTFSREAD" driver (version 1.200) for DR-DOS 7.0x between 2002 and 2004.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] It was part of their Nero Burning ROM software.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS uses access control lists and user-level encryption to help secure user data.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] In NTFS, each file or folder is assigned a security descriptor that defines its owner and contains two access control lists (ACLs).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The first ACL, called discretionary access control list (DACL), defines exactly what type of interactions (e.g. reading, writing, executing or deleting) are allowed or forbidden by which user or groups of users.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] For example, files in the `C:\Program Files` folder may be read and executed by all users but modified only by a user holding administrative privileges.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Windows Vista adds mandatory access control info to DACLs.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] DACLs are the primary focus of User Account Control in Windows Vista and later.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The second ACL, called system access control list (SACL), defines which interactions with the file or folder are to be audited and whether they should be logged when the activity is successful, failed or both.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] For example, auditing can be enabled on sensitive files of a company, so that its managers get to know when someone tries to delete them or make a copy of them, and whether they succeed.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Encrypting File System (EFS) provides user-transparent encryption of any file or folder on an NTFS volume.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] EFS works in conjunction with the EFS service, Microsoft's CryptoAPI and the EFS File System Run-Time Library (FSRTL).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] EFS works by encrypting a file with a bulk symmetric key (also known as the File Encryption Key, or FEK), which is used because it takes a relatively small amount of time to encrypt and decrypt large amounts of data than if an asymmetric key cipher is used.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The symmetric key that is used to encrypt the file is then encrypted with a public key that is associated with the user who encrypted the file, and this encrypted data is stored in an alternate data stream of the encrypted file.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] To decrypt the file, the file system uses the private key of the user to decrypt the symmetric key that is stored in the data stream.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] It then uses the symmetric key to decrypt the file.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Because this is done at the file system level, it is transparent to the user.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Also, in case of a user losing access to their key, support for additional decryption keys has been built into the EFS system, so that a recovery agent can still access the files if needed.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS-provided encryption and NTFS-provided compression are mutually exclusive, meaning they can not be used for the same files at the same time; however, NTFS can be used for one and a third-party tool for the other.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The support of EFS is not available in Basic, Home, and MediaCenter versions of Windows, and must be activated after installation of Professional, Ultimate, and Server versions of Windows or by using enterprise deployment tools within Windows domains.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS is a journaling file system and uses the NTFS Log ($LogFile) to record metadata changes to the volume.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Notably affected structures are the volume allocation bitmap, modifications to MFT records such as moves of some variable-length attributes stored in MFT records and attribute lists, and indices for directories and security descriptors.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The incompatibility of the $LogFile versions implemented by Windows 8, Windows 10, Windows 11 prevents Windows 7 (and earlier versions of Windows) from recognizing version 2.0 of the $LogFile.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Backward compatibility is provided by downgrading the $LogFile to version 1.1 when an NTFS volume is cleanly dismounted.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] It is again upgraded to version 2.0 when mounting on a compatible version of Windows.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] However, when hibernating to disk in the logoff state (a.k.a.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Hybrid Boot or Fast Boot, which is enabled by default), mounted file systems are not dismounted, and thus the $LogFiles of any active file systems are not downgraded to version 1.1.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The inability to process version 2.0 of the $LogFile by versions of Windows older than 8.0 results in an unnecessary invocation of the CHKDSK disk repair utility.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This is particularly a concern in a multi-boot scenario involving pre- and post-8.0 versions of Windows, or when frequently moving a storage device between older and newer versions.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] A Windows Registry setting exists to prevent the automatic upgrade of the $LogFile to the newer version.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The problem can also be dealt with by disabling Hybrid Boot.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The USN Journal (Update Sequence Number Journal) is a system management feature that records (in $Extend\$UsnJrnl) changes to files, streams and directories on the volume, as well as their various attributes and security settings.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The journal is made available for applications to track changes to the volume.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This journal can be enabled or disabled on non-system volumes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The hard link feature allows different file names to directly refer to the same file contents.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Hard links may link only to files in the same volume, because each volume has its own MFT.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Hard links were originally included to support the POSIX subsystem in Windows NT.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Although hard links use the same MFT record (inode) which records file metadata such as file size, modification date, and attributes, NTFS also caches this data in the directory entry as a performance enhancement.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This means that when listing the contents of a directory using FindFirstFile/FindNextFile family of APIs, (equivalent to the POSIX opendir/readdir APIs) the software listing the directory will also receive this cached information, in addition to the name and inode.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] However, software may not see up-to-date information, as this information is only guaranteed to be updated when a file is closed, and then only for the directory from which the file was opened.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This means where a file has multiple names via hard links, updating a file via one name does not update the cached data associated with the other name.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Software can obtain up-to-date data using GetFileInformationByHandle (which is the equivalent of the POSIX fstat function).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This can be done using a handle which has no access to the file itself (passing zero to CreateFile for dwDesiredAccess), and closing this handle has the incidental effect of updating the cached information.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Windows uses hard links to support short (8.3) filenames in NTFS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Operating system support is needed because there are legacy applications that can work only with 8.3 filenames, but support can be disabled.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] In this case, an additional filename record and directory entry is added, but both 8.3 and long file name are linked and updated together, unlike a regular hard link.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The NTFS file system has a limit of 1023 hard links on a file.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Alternate data streams allow more than one data stream to be associated with a filename (a fork), using the format "filename:streamname" (e.g., "text.txt:extrastream").
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] These streams are not shown to or made editable by users through any typical GUI application built into Windows by default, disguising their existence from most users.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Although intended for helpful metadata, their arcane nature makes them a potential hiding place for malware, spyware, unseen browser history, and other potentially unwanted information.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Alternate streams are not listed in Windows Explorer, and their size is not included in the file's size.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] When the file is copied or moved to another file system without ADS support the user is warned that alternate data streams cannot be preserved.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] No such warning is typically provided if the file is attached to an e-mail, or uploaded to a website.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Thus, using alternate streams for critical data may cause problems.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Microsoft provides a downloadable tool called Streams to view streams on a selected volume.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Starting with Windows PowerShell 3.0, it is possible to manage ADS natively with six cmdlets: Add-Content, Clear-Content, Get-Content, Get-Item, Remove-Item, Set-Content.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] A small ADS named `Zone.Identifier` is added by Internet Explorer and by most browsers to mark files downloaded from external sites as possibly unsafe to run; the local shell would then require user confirmation before opening them.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] When the user indicates that they no longer want this confirmation dialog, this ADS is deleted.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This functionality is also known as "Mark of the Web".
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Google Chrome) and Firefox-based web browsers also write the `Zone.Identifier` stream to downloaded files.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Malware has used alternate data streams to hide code.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Since the late 2000s, some malware scanners and other special tools check for alternate data streams.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Due to the risks associated with ADS, particularly involving privacy and the `Zone.Identifier` stream, there exists software specifically designed to strip streams from files (certain streams with perceived risk or all of them) in a user-friendly way.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS Streams were introduced in Windows NT 3.1, to enable Services for Macintosh (SFM) to store resource forks.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Although current versions of Windows Server no longer include SFM, third-party Apple Filing Protocol (AFP) products (such as GroupLogic's ExtremeZ-IP) still use this feature of the file system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Compression is enabled on a per-folder or per-file basis by setting the 'compressed' attribute.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] When compression is enabled on a folder, any files moved or saved to that folder will be automatically compressed using LZNT1 algorithm (a variant of LZ77).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The compression algorithm is designed to support cluster sizes of up to 4 KB; when the cluster size is greater than 4 KB on an NTFS volume, NTFS compression is not available.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Data is compressed in 16-cluster chunks (up to 64 KB in size); if the compression reduces 64 KB of data to 60 KB or less, NTFS treats the unneeded 4 KB pages like empty sparse file clusters—they are not written.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This allows for reasonable random-access times as the OS merely has to follow the chain of fragments.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Compression works best with files that have repetitive content, are seldom written, are usually accessed sequentially, and are not themselves compressed.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Single-user systems with limited hard disk space can benefit from NTFS compression for small files, from 4 KB to 64 KB or more, depending on compressibility.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Files smaller than approximately 900 bytes are stored within the directory entry of the MFT.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] For operating systems besides Windows, all versions of the NTFS-3G driver support reading compressed files according to its developers, but support for appending data to compressed files, which means adding new data resulting in increasing the size of a file, was added in November 2009.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Overwriting existing compressed data is supported since August 2010.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Various programs utilize NTFS file compression, such as CompactGUI.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Users of fast multi-core processors will find improvements in application speed by compressing their applications and data as well as a reduction in space used.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Even when SSD controllers already compress data, there is still a reduction in I/Os since less data is transferred.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] According to research by Microsoft's NTFS Development team, 50–60 GB is a reasonable maximum size for a compressed file on an NTFS volume with a 4 KB (default) cluster (block) size.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This reasonable maximum size decreases sharply for volumes with smaller cluster sizes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Large compressible files become highly fragmented since every chunk smaller than 64 KB becomes a fragment.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Flash memory, such as SSD drives do not have the head movement delays and high access time of mechanical hard disk drives, so fragmentation has only a smaller penalty.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Windows 2000 cannot start if NTLDR is compressed because decompression filters are not yet loaded.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Later versions of Windows do not allow important system files to be compressed.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Since Windows 10, Microsoft has introduced new file compression scheme based on the XPRESS algorithm with 4K/8K/16K block size and the LZX algorithm; both are variants of LZ77 updated with Huffman entropy coding and range coding, which LZNT1 lacked.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] These compression algorithms were taken from Windows Imaging Format (WIM file).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The new compression scheme is used by CompactOS feature, which reduces disk usage by compressing Windows system files.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This design is meant purely for read-only access, so any writes to compressed files result in an automatic decompression.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] CompactOS compression is intended for OEMs who prepare OS images with the `/compact` flag of the `DISM` tool in Windows ADK, but it can also be manually turned on per file with the `/exe` flag of the `compact` command.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] CompactOS algorithm avoids file fragmentation by writing compressed data in contiguously allocated chunks, unlike core NTFS compression.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] CompactOS file compression is an improved version of WIMBoot feature introduced in Windows 8.1.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] WIMBoot reduces Windows disk usage by keeping system files in a compressed WIM image on a separate hidden disk partition.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Similarly to CompactOS, Windows system directories only contain sparse files marked by a reparse point with a WOF tag, and Windows Overlay Filter driver decompresses file contents on-the-fly from the WIM image.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] WIMBoot is less effective than CompactOS though, as new updated versions of system files need to be written to the system partition, consuming disk space.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Sparse files are files interspersed with empty segments for which no actual storage space is used.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] To the applications, the file looks like an ordinary file with empty regions seen as regions filled with zeros; the file system maintains an internal list of such regions for each sparse file.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] A sparse file does not necessarily include sparse zeros areas; the "sparse file" attribute just means that the file is allowed to have them.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Database applications, for instance, may use sparse files.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] As with compressed files, the actual sizes of sparse files are not taken into account when determining quota limits.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The Volume Shadow Copy Service (VSS) keeps historical versions of files and folders on NTFS volumes by copying old, newly overwritten data to shadow copy via copy-on-write technique.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The user may later request an earlier version to be recovered.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This also allows data backup programs to archive files currently in use by the file system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Windows Vista also introduced persistent shadow copies for use with System Restore and Previous Versions features.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Persistent shadow copies, however, are deleted when an older operating system mounts that NTFS volume.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] This happens because the older operating system does not understand the newer format of persistent shadow copies.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] As of Windows Vista, applications can use Transactional NTFS (TxF) to group multiple changes to files together into a single transaction.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The transaction will guarantee that either all of the changes happen, or none of them do, and that no application outside the transaction will see the changes until they are committed.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Transactional NTFS does not restrict transactions to just the local NTFS volume, but also includes other transactional data or operations in other locations such as data stored in separate volumes, the local registry, or SQL databases, or the current states of system services or remote services.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Transactional NTFS allows, for example, the creation of network-wide consistent distributed file systems, including with their local live or offline caches.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Microsoft now advises against using TxF: "Microsoft strongly recommends developers utilize alternative means" since "TxF may not be available in future versions of Microsoft Windows".
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] They allow the administrator of a computer that runs a version of Windows that supports NTFS to set a threshold of disk space that users may use.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] It also allows administrators to keep track of how much disk space each user is using.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] An administrator may specify a certain level of disk space that a user may use before they receive a warning, and then deny access to the user once they hit their upper limit of space.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Disk quotas do not take into account NTFS's transparent file-compression, should this be enabled.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Applications that query the amount of free space will also see the amount of free space left to the user who has a quota applied to them.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Introduced in NTFS v3, NTFS reparse points are used by associating a reparse tag in the user space attribute of a file or directory.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Microsoft includes several default tags including symbolic links, directory junction points and volume mount points.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] When the Object Manager parses a file system name lookup and encounters a reparse attribute, it will *reparse* the name lookup, passing the user controlled reparse data to every file system filter driver that is loaded into Windows.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Each filter driver examines the reparse data to see whether it is associated with that reparse point, and if that filter driver determines a match, then it intercepts the file system request and performs its special functionality.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS stores date and time attributes as a 64-bit integer that counts the 100-nanosecond intervals from the beginning of the year 1601, following the Windows NT epoch.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] The year 1601 was chosen to align the beginning of the date range with the gregorian calendar in order to simplify calculations, given that the gregorian calendar operates on a 400-year cycle, and the 1601-2000 cycle was the active cycle at the time Windows NT was conceived.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] NTFS records four types of time stamps: A file creation time (interpreted as "birth time" on Linux), a last modification time, a last modification of the MFT record (interpreted as "change time" on Linux) and a last access time.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Each of those times has the same granularity of 100 nanoseconds.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Starting with Windows Vista, Microsoft added the built-in ability to shrink or expand a partition.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] However, this ability does not relocate page file fragments or files that have been marked as unmovable, so shrinking a volume will often require relocating or disabling any page file, the index of Windows Search, and any Shadow Copy used by System Restore.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Various third-party tools are capable of resizing NTFS partitions.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p01] Since 2017, Microsoft requires the OneDrive file structure to reside on an NTFS disk.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Internally, NTFS uses B-trees to index file system data.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] A file system journal is used to guarantee the integrity of the file system metadata but not individual files' content.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Systems using NTFS are known to have improved reliability compared to FAT file systems.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] NTFS allows any sequence of 16-bit values for name encoding (e.g. file names, stream names or index names) except 0x0000.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] This means UTF-16 code units are supported, but the file system does not check whether a sequence is valid UTF-16 (it allows any sequence of short values, not restricted to those in the Unicode standard).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] In Win32 namespace, any UTF-16 code units are case insensitive whereas in POSIX namespace they are case sensitive.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] File names are limited to 255 UTF-16 code units.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Certain names are reserved in the volume root directory and cannot be used for files.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] `.` (dot) and `$Extend` are both directories; the others are files.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] The NT kernel limits full paths to 32,767 UTF-16 code units.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] There are some additional restrictions on code points and file names.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] This boot partition format is roughly based upon the earlier FAT filesystem, but the fields are in different locations.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Some of these fields, especially the "sectors per track", "number of heads" and "hidden sectors" fields may contain dummy values on drives where they either do not make sense or are not determinable.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] The OS first looks at the 8 bytes at 0x30 to find the cluster number of the $MFT, then multiplies that number by the number of sectors per cluster (1 byte found at 0x0D).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] This value is the sector offset (LBA) to the $MFT, which is described below.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] In NTFS, all file, directory and metafile data—file name, creation date, access permissions (by the use of access control lists), and size—are stored as metadata in the **Master File Table** (**MFT**).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] This abstract approach allowed easy addition of file system features during Windows NT's development—an example is the addition of fields for indexing used by the Active Directory and the Windows Search.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] This also enables fast file search software to locate named local files and folders included in the MFT very quickly, without requiring any other index.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] The MFT structure supports algorithms which minimize disk fragmentation.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] A directory entry consists of a filename and a "file ID" (analogous to the inode number), which is the record number representing the file in the Master File Table.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] The file ID also contains a reuse count to detect stale references.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] While this strongly resembles the W_FID of Files-11, other NTFS structures radically differ.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] A partial copy of the MFT, called the MFT mirror, is stored to be used in case of corruption.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] If the first record of the MFT is corrupted, NTFS reads the second record to find the MFT mirror file.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Locations for both files are stored in the boot sector.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] NTFS contains several files that define and organize the file system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] In all respects, most of these files are structured like any other user file ($Volume being the most peculiar), but are not of direct interest to file system clients.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] These metafiles define files, back up critical file system data, buffer file system changes, manage free space allocation, satisfy BIOS expectations, track bad allocation units, and store security and disk space usage information.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] All content is in an unnamed data stream, unless otherwise indicated.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] These metafiles are treated specially by Windows, handled directly by the `NTFS.SYS` driver and are difficult to directly view: special purpose-built tools are needed.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] As of Windows 7, the NTFS driver completely prohibits user access, resulting in a BSoD whenever an attempt to execute a metadata file is made.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] One such tool is the nfi.exe ("NTFS File Sector Information Utility") that is freely distributed as part of the Microsoft "OEM Support Tools".
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] For example, to obtain information on the "$MFT"-Master File Table Segment the following command is used: `nfi.exe c:\$MFT` Another way to bypass the restriction is to use 7-Zip's file manager and go to the low-level NTFS path `\\.\X:\` (where `X:\` resembles any drive/partition).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Here, 3 new folders will appear: `$EXTEND`, `[DELETED]` (a pseudo-folder that 7-Zip uses to attach files deleted from the file system to view), and `[SYSTEM]` (another pseudo-folder that contains all the NTFS metadata files).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] This trick can be used from removable devices (USB flash drives, external hard drives, SD cards, etc.) inside Windows, but doing this on the active partition requires offline access (namely WinRE).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Each attribute has an attribute type (a fixed-size integer mapping to an attribute definition in file $AttrDef), an optional attribute name (for example, used as the name for an alternate data stream), and a value, represented in a sequence of bytes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] For NTFS, the standard data of files, the alternate data streams, or the index data for directories are stored as attributes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] According to $AttrDef, some attributes can be either resident or non-resident.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] The $DATA attribute, which contains file data, is such an example.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] When the attribute is resident (which is represented by a flag), its value is stored directly in the MFT record.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Otherwise, clusters are allocated for the data, and the cluster location information is stored as data runs in the attribute.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] All attributes of a given file may be displayed by using the nfi.exe ("NTFS File Sector Information Utility") that is freely distributed as part of the Microsoft "OEM Support Tools".
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Windows system calls may handle alternate data streams.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Depending on the operating system, utility and remote file system, a file transfer might silently strip data streams.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] A safe way of copying or moving files is to use the BackupRead and BackupWrite system calls, which allow programs to enumerate streams, to verify whether each stream should be written to the destination volume and to knowingly skip unwanted streams.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] When the value can be accessed directly from within the attribute, it is called "resident data" (by computer forensics workers).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] The amount of data that fits is highly dependent on the file's characteristics, but 700 to 800 bytes is common in single-stream files with non-lengthy filenames and no ACLs.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] The allocation map is stored in a form of *data runs* with compressed encoding.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Each data run represents a contiguous group of clusters that store the attribute value.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] For files on a multi-GB volume, each entry can be encoded as 5 to 7 bytes, which means a 1 KB MFT record can store about 100 such data runs.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] However, as the $ATTRIBUTE_LIST also has a size limit, it is dangerous to have more than 1 million fragments of a single file on an NTFS volume, which also implies that it is in general not a good idea to use NTFS compression on a file larger than 10 GB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Since resident files do not directly occupy clusters ("allocation units"), it is possible for an NTFS volume to contain more files on a volume than there are clusters.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] For example, a 74.5 GB partition NTFS formats with 19,543,064 clusters of 4 KB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Subtracting system files (a 64 MB log file, a 2,442,888-byte Bitmap file, and about 25 clusters of fixed overhead) leaves 19,526,158 clusters free for files and indices.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Since there are four MFT records per cluster, this volume theoretically could hold almost 4 × 19,526,158 = 78,104,632 resident files.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Opportunistic file locks (oplocks) allow clients to alter their buffering strategy for a given file or stream in order to increase performance and reduce network use.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Oplocks apply to the given open stream of a file and do not affect oplocks on a different stream.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Oplocks can be used to transparently access files in the background.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] A network client may avoid writing information into a file on a remote server if no other process is accessing the data, or it may buffer read-ahead data if no other process is writing data.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Opportunistic locks have been enhanced in Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 with per-client oplock keys.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Windows NT and its descendants keep internal timestamps as UTC and make the appropriate conversions for display purposes; all NTFS timestamps are in UTC.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] For historical reasons, the versions of Windows that do not support NTFS all keep time internally as local zone time, and therefore so does the FAT file system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] This means that when files are copied or moved between NTFS and FAT partitions, the OS needs to convert timestamps on the fly.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] But if some files are moved when daylight saving time (DST) is in effect, and other files are moved when standard time is in effect, there can be some ambiguities in the conversions.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] As a result, especially shortly after one of the days on which local zone time changes, users may observe that some files have timestamps that are incorrect by one hour.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] Due to the differences in implementation of DST in different jurisdictions, this can result in a potential timestamp error of up to 4 hours in any given 12 months.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/alternate-data-streams-p02] This problem is further exacerbated for any computers for which local time zone changes sometimes (e.g. due to moving the computer from one time zone to another, as often happens with laptops and other portable devices).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT was replaced with NTFS as the default file system on Microsoft operating systems starting with Windows XP.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Nevertheless, FAT continues to be commonly used on relatively small capacity solid-state storage technologies such as USB flash drives, SD cards, MultiMediaCards (MMC) and eMMC because of its compatibility across operating systems and embedded systems, and ease of implementation.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT was used on hard disks throughout the DOS and Windows 9x eras.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Microsoft introduced NTFS with the Windows NT platform in 1993, but FAT remained the standard for the home user until the introduction of Windows XP in 2001.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Windows Me was the final version of Windows to use FAT as its default file system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] For floppy disks, FAT has been standardized as ECMA-107 and ISO/IEC 9293:1994 (superseding ISO 9293:1987).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] These standards cover FAT12 and FAT16 with only short 8.3 filename support; long filenames with VFAT were partially patented.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] While FAT12 is used on floppy disks, FAT16 and FAT32 are typically found on the larger media.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT is used internally for the EFI system partition in the boot stage of EFI-compliant computers.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT is still used in drives expected to be used by multiple operating systems, such as in shared Windows and Linux environments.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Microsoft Windows additionally comes with a pre-installed tool to convert a FAT file system into NTFS directly without the need to rewrite all files, though this cannot be reversed easily.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The FAT file system is used in removable media such as floppy disks, super-floppies, memory and flash memory cards or USB flash drives.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT is supported by portable devices such as PDAs, digital cameras, camcorders, media players, mobile phones, game consoles, as well as embedded systems such as boomboxes and DVD players and vehicle audio systems with built-in USB ports and SD card readers.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The DCF file system adopted by almost all digital cameras since 1998 defines a logical file system with 8.3 filenames and makes the use of either FAT12, FAT16, FAT32 or exFAT mandatory for its physical layer for compatibility.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The file system uses an index table stored on the device to identify chains of data storage areas associated with a file, the *File Allocation Table* (*FAT*).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The FAT is statically allocated at the time of formatting.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The table is a linked list of entries for each *cluster*, a contiguous area of disk storage.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Each entry contains either the number of the next cluster in the file, or else a marker indicating the end of the file, unused disk space, or special reserved areas of the disk.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The *root directory* of the disk contains the number of the first cluster of each file in that directory.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The operating system can then traverse the FAT, looking up the cluster number of each successive part of the disk file as a *cluster chain* until the end of the file is reached.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] *Sub-directories* are implemented as special files containing the *directory entries* of their respective files.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Each entry in the FAT linked list is a fixed number of bits: 12, 16 or 32.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The maximum size of a file or a disk drive that can be accessed is the product of the largest number that can be stored in the entries (less a few values reserved to indicate unallocated space or the end of a list) and the size of the disk cluster.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Even if only one byte of storage is needed to extend a file, an entire cluster must be allocated to it.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] As a result, large numbers of small files can result in clusters being allocated that may contain mostly "empty" data to meet the minimum cluster size.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Originally designed as an 8-bit file system, the maximum number of clusters must increase as disk drive capacity increases, and so the number of bits used to identify each cluster has grown.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The successive major variants of the FAT format are named after the number of table element bits: 12 (FAT12), 16 (FAT16), and 32 (FAT32).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] There are several variants of the FAT file system (e.g.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT16 refers to both the original group of FAT file systems with 16-bit wide cluster entries and also to later variants.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] "VFAT" is an optional extension for long file names, which can work on top of any FAT file system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Volumes using VFAT long-filenames can be read also by operating systems not supporting the VFAT extension.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The original FAT file system (or *FAT structure*, as it was called initially) was designed and implemented by Marc McDonald, based on a series of discussions between McDonald and Bill Gates.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] It was introduced with 8-bit table elements (and valid data cluster numbers up to `0xBF`) in a precursor to Microsoft's *Standalone Disk BASIC-80* for an 8080-based successor of the NCR 7200 model VI data-entry terminal, equipped with 8-inch (200 mm) floppy disks, in 1977 or 1978.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In 1978, *Standalone Disk BASIC-80* was ported to the 8086 using an emulator on a DEC PDP-10, since no real 8086 systems were available at this time.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The FAT file system was also used in Microsoft's MDOS/MIDAS, an operating system for 8080/Z80 platforms written by McDonald since 1979.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The *Standalone Disk BASIC* version supported three FATs, whereas this was a parameter for MIDAS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Reportedly, MIDAS was also prepared to support 10-bit, 12-bit and 16-bit FAT variants.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] While the size of directory entries was 16 bytes in *Standalone Disk BASIC*, MIDAS instead occupied 32 bytes per entry.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Tim Paterson of Seattle Computer Products (SCP) was first introduced to Microsoft's FAT structure when he helped Bob O'Rear adapting the *Standalone Disk BASIC-86* emulator port onto SCP's S-100 bus 8086 CPU board prototype during a guest week at Microsoft in May 1979.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The final product was shown at Lifeboat Associates' booth stand at the National Computer Conference in New York on June 4–7, 1979, where Paterson learned about the more sophisticated FAT implementation in MDOS/MIDAS and McDonald talked to him about the design of the file system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Paterson also increased the nine-character (6.3) filename length limit to eleven characters to support CP/M-style 8.3 filenames and File Control Blocks.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The format used in Microsoft *Standalone Disk BASIC's* 8-bit file system precursor was not supported by QDOS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] By August 1980, QDOS had been renamed to 86-DOS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Starting with 86-DOS 0.42, the size and layout of directory entries was changed from 16 bytes to 32 bytes in order to add a file date stamp and increase the theoretical file size limit beyond the previous limit of 16 MB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] 86-DOS 1.00 became available in early 1981.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Later in 1981, 86-DOS evolved into Microsoft's MS-DOS and IBM PC DOS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The capability to read previously formatted volumes with 16-byte directory entries was dropped with MS-DOS 1.20.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT12 used 12-bit entries for the cluster addresses; some values were reserved to mark the end of a chain of clusters, to mark unusable areas of the disk, or for other purposes, so the maximum number of clusters was limited to 4078.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] To conserve disk space, two 12-bit FAT entries used three consecutive 8-bit bytes on disk, requiring manipulation to unpack the 12-bit values.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] This was sufficient for the original floppy disk drives, and small hard disks up to 32 megabytes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The FAT16B version available with DOS 3.31 supported 32-bit sector numbers, and so increased the volume size limit.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] All the control structures fit inside the first track, to avoid head movement during read and write operations.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Any bad sector in the control structures area would make the disk unusable.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The DOS formatting tool rejected such disks completely.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Bad sectors were allowed only in the file data area.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Clusters containing bad sectors were marked unusable with the reserved value `0xFF7` in the FAT.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] PC DOS 2.0 introduced support for 9-sector floppy formats with 180 KB (FAT ID `0xFC`) and 360 KB (FAT ID `0xFD`).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] 86-DOS 1.00 and PC DOS 1.0 directory entries included only one date, the last modified date.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] PC DOS 1.1 added the last modified time.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] PC DOS 1.x file attributes included a hidden bit and system bit, with the remaining six bits undefined.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] At this time, DOS did not support sub-directories, but typically there were only a few dozen files on a diskette.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The PC XT was the first PC with an IBM-supplied hard drive, and PC DOS 2.0 supported that hard drive with FAT12 (FAT ID `0xF8`).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The fixed assumption of 8 sectors per clusters on hard disks practically limited the maximum partition size to 16 MB for 512 byte sectors and 4 KB clusters.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The *BIOS Parameter Block* (*BPB*) was introduced with PC DOS 2.0 as well, and this version also added read-only, archive, volume label, and directory attribute bits for hierarchical sub-directories.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] MS-DOS 3.0 introduced support for high-density 1.2 MB 5.25-inch diskettes (media descriptor `0xF9`), which notably had 15 sectors per track, hence more space for the FATs.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT12 remains in use on all common floppy disks, including 1.44 MB and later 2.88 MB disks (media descriptor byte `0xF0`).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In 1984, IBM released the PC AT, which required PC DOS 3.0 to access its 20 MB hard disk.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Microsoft introduced MS-DOS 3.0 in parallel.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Cluster addresses were increased to 16-bit, allowing for up to 65,526 clusters per volume.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] However, the maximum possible number of sectors and the maximum partition size of 32 MB did not change.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Although cluster addresses were 16 bits, this format was not what today is commonly understood as **FAT16**.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] A partition type `0x04` indicates this form of FAT16 with less than 65,536 sectors (less than 32 MB for sector size 512).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The benefit of FAT16 was the use of smaller clusters, making disk usage more efficient, particularly for large numbers of files only a few hundred bytes in size.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] As MS-DOS 3.0 formatted all 16 MB-32 MB partitions in the FAT16 format, a 20 MB hard disk formatted under MS-DOS 3.0 was not accessible by MS-DOS 2.0.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] MS-DOS 3.0 to MS-DOS 3.30 could still access FAT12 partitions under 15 MB, but required all 16 MB-32 MB partitions to be FAT16, and so could not access MS-DOS 2.0 partitions in this size range.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] MS-DOS 3.31 and higher could access 16 MB-32 MB FAT12 partitions again.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] MS-DOS and PC DOS implementations of FAT12 and FAT16 could not access disk partitions larger than 32 megabytes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Several manufacturers developed their own FAT variants within their OEM versions of MS-DOS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Some vendors (AST and NEC) supported eight, instead of the standard four, primary partition entries in their custom extended *Master Boot Record* (*MBR*), and they adapted MS-DOS to use more than a single primary partition.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Other vendors worked around the volume size limits imposed by the 16-bit sector entries by increasing the apparent *size* of the sectors the file system operated on.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] These *logical sectors* were larger (up to 8192 bytes) than the *physical sector* size (still 512 bytes) on the disk.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The DOS-BIOS or System BIOS would then combine multiple physical sectors into logical sectors for the file system to work with.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] These changes were transparent to the file system implementation in the DOS kernel.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The underlying DOS-BIOS translated these logical sectors into physical sectors according to partitioning information and the drive's physical geometry.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The drawback of this approach was increased memory used for sector buffering and deblocking.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Since older DOS versions could not use large logical sectors, the OEMs introduced new partition IDs for their FAT variants in order to hide them from off-the-shelf issues of MS-DOS and PC DOS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] OEM versions like Toshiba MS-DOS, Wyse MS-DOS 3.2 and 3.3, as well as Zenith MS-DOS are also known to have utilized logical sectoring.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] While non-standard and sub-optimal, these FAT variants are perfectly valid according to the specifications of the file system itself.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] A parallel development in MS-DOS / PC DOS which allowed an increase in the maximum possible disk size was the extension of the number of FAT partitions on a hard disk beyond the earlier 4, and the replacement of "installable block devices" with native DOS FAT partitions.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] To allow the use of more FAT partitions in a compatible way, a new partition type was introduced in PC DOS 3.2 (1986), the *extended partition* (EBR), which is a container for an additional partition called *logical drive*.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Since PC DOS 3.3 (April 1987), there is another, optional extended partition containing the next *logical drive*, and so on.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The MBR of a hard disk can either define up to four primary partitions, or an extended partition in addition to up to three primary partitions.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In November 1987, Compaq Personal Computer DOS 3.31 (a modified OEM version of MS-DOS 3.3 released by Compaq with their machines) introduced what today is simply known as *the FAT16* format, with the expansion of the 16-bit disk sector count to 32 bits in the BPB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Although the on-disk changes were minor, the entire DOS disk driver had to be converted to use 32-bit sector numbers, a task complicated by the fact that it was written in 16-bit assembly language.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The result was initially called the *DOS 3.31 Large File System*.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Microsoft's `DSKPROBE` tool refers to type `0x06` as *BigFAT*, whereas some older versions of `FDISK` described it as *BIGDOS*.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Since older versions of DOS were not designed to cope with more than 65,535 sectors, it was necessary to introduce a new partition type for this format in order to hide it from pre-3.31 issues of DOS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The original form of FAT16 (with less than 65,536 sectors) had a partition type `0x04`.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] To deal with disks larger than this, type `0x06` was introduced to indicate 65,536 or more sectors.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In addition to this, the disk driver was expanded to cope with more than 65,535 sectors as well.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The only other difference between the original FAT16 and the newer FAT16B format is the usage of a newer BPB format with 32-bit sector entry.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Therefore, newer operating systems supporting the FAT16B format can cope also with the original FAT16 format without any necessary changes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] If partitions to be used by pre-DOS 3.31 issues of DOS need to be created by modern tools, the only criteria theoretically necessary to meet are a sector count of less than 65536, and the usage of the old partition ID (`0x04`).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In practice however, type `0x01` and `0x04` primary partitions should not be physically located outside the first 32 MB of the disk, due to other restrictions in MS-DOS 2.x, which could not cope with them otherwise.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In 1988, the FAT16B improvement became more generally available through DR DOS 3.31, PC DOS 4.0, OS/2 1.1, and MS-DOS 4.0.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The limit on partition size was dictated by the 8-bit signed count of sectors per cluster, which originally had a maximum power-of-two value of 64.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] With the standard hard disk sector size of 512 bytes, this gives a maximum of 32 KB cluster size, thereby fixing the "definitive" limit for the FAT16 partition size at 2 GB for sector size 512.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] On magneto-optical media, which can have 1 or 2 KB sectors instead of 0.5 KB, this size limit is proportionally larger.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Much later, Windows NT increased the maximum cluster size to 64 KB, by considering the sectors-per-cluster count as unsigned.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] However, the resulting format was not compatible with any other FAT implementation of the time, and it generated greater internal fragmentation.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Windows 98, SE and ME also supported reading and writing this variant, but its disk utilities did not work with it and some FCB services are not available for such volumes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] This contributes to a confusing compatibility situation.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Prior to 1995, versions of DOS accessed the disk via CHS addressing only.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] When Windows 95 (MS-DOS 7.0) introduced LBA disk access, partitions could start being physically located outside the first c.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] 8 GB of this disk and thereby out of the reach of the traditional CHS addressing scheme.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Partitions partially or fully located beyond the CHS barrier therefore had to be hidden from non-LBA-enabled operating systems by using the new partition type `0x0E` in the partition table instead.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT16 partitions using this partition type are also named **FAT16X**.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The only difference, compared to previous FAT16 partitions, is the fact that some CHS-related geometry entries in the BPB record, namely the number of sectors per track and the number of heads, may contain no or misleading values and should not be used.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The number of root directory entries available for FAT12 and FAT16 is determined when the volume is formatted, and is stored in a 16-bit field.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] For a given number `RDE` and sector size `SS`, the number `RDS` of root directory sectors is `RDS = ceil((RDE × 32) / SS)`, and `RDE` is normally chosen to fill these sectors, i.e., `RDE × 32 = RDS × SS`.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT12 and FAT16 media typically use 512 root directory entries on non-floppy media.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Some third-party tools, like mkdosfs, allow the user to set this parameter.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Cluster values are represented by 32-bit numbers, of which 28 bits are used to hold the cluster number.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The FAT32 boot sector uses a 32-bit field for the sector count, limiting the maximal FAT32 volume size to 2 terabytes with a sector size of 512 bytes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The maximum FAT32 volume size is 16 TB with a sector size of 4,096 bytes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In August 2024, Microsoft released an update to Windows 11 preview builds that allows for the creation of FAT32 partitions up to 2TB in size.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The maximal possible size for a file on a FAT32 volume is 4 GB minus 1 byte, or 4,294,967,295 (232 − 1) bytes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] This limit is a consequence of the 4-byte file length entry in the directory table and would also affect relatively huge FAT16 partitions enabled by a sufficient sector size.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Like FAT12 and FAT16, FAT32 does not include direct built-in support for long filenames, but FAT32 volumes can optionally hold VFAT long filenames in addition to short filenames in exactly the same way as VFAT long filenames have been optionally implemented for FAT12 and FAT16 volumes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FAT32 was introduced with Windows 95 OSR2 (MS-DOS 7.1) in 1996, although reformatting was needed to use it, and DriveSpace 3 (the version that came with Windows 95 OSR2 and Windows 98) never supported it.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Windows 98 introduced a utility to convert existing hard disks from FAT16 to FAT32 without loss of data.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In the Windows NT line, native support for FAT32 arrived in Windows 2000.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] A free FAT32 driver for Windows NT 4.0 was available from Winternals, a company later acquired by Microsoft.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The acquisition of the driver from official sources is no longer possible.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Since 1998, Caldera's dynamically loadable DRFAT32 driver could be used to enable FAT32 support in DR-DOS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The first version of DR-DOS to natively support FAT32 and LBA access was OEM DR-DOS 7.04 in 1999.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] That same year IMS introduced native FAT32 support with REAL/32 7.90, and IBM 4690 OS added FAT32 support with version 2.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Ahead Software provided another dynamically loadable FAT32.EXE driver for DR-DOS 7.03 with Nero Burning ROM in 2004.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] IBM introduced native FAT32 support with OEM PC DOS 7.1 in 1999.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Two partition types have been reserved for FAT32 partitions, `0x0B` and `0x0C`.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The latter type is also named **FAT32X** in order to indicate usage of LBA disk access instead of CHS.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] On such partitions, CHS-related geometry entries, namely the CHS sector addresses in the MBR as well as the number of sectors per track and the number of heads in the EBPB record, may contain no or misleading values and should not be used.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] OS/2 heavily depends on extended attributes (EAs) and stores them in a hidden file called "`EA␠DATA.␠SF`" in the root directory of the FAT12 or FAT16 volume.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] This file is indexed by two previously reserved bytes in the file's (or directory's) directory entry at offset `0x14`.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In the FAT32 format, these bytes hold the upper 16 bits of the starting cluster number of the file or directory, hence making it impossible to store OS/2 EAs on FAT32 using this method.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The driver also utilizes the byte at offset `0x0C` in directory entries to store a special mark byte indicating the presence of extended attributes to help speed up things.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Extended attributes are accessible via the Workplace Shell desktop, through REXX scripts, and many system GUI and command-line utilities (such as 4OS2).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] To accommodate its OS/2 subsystem, Windows NT supports the handling of extended attributes in HPFS, NTFS, FAT12 and FAT16.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] It stores EAs on FAT12, FAT16 and HPFS using exactly the same scheme as OS/2, but does not support any other kind of ADS as held on NTFS volumes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Trying to copy a file with any ADS other than EAs from an NTFS volume to a FAT or HPFS volume gives a warning message with the names of the ADSs that will be lost.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] It does not support the FAT32.IFS method to store EAs on FAT32 volumes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Windows 2000 onward acts exactly as Windows NT, except that it ignores EAs when copying to FAT32 without any warning (but shows the warning for other ADSs, like "Macintosh Finder Info" and "Macintosh Resource Fork").
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Cygwin uses "`EA␠DATA.␠SF`" files as well.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] One of the user experience goals for the designers of Windows 95 was the ability to use long filenames (LFNs—up to 255 UCS-2 code units long), in addition to classic 8.3 filenames (SFNs).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] For backward and forward compatibility, LFNs were implemented as an optional extension on top of the existing FAT file system structures using a workaround in the way directory entries are laid out.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] This transparent method to store long file names in the existing FAT file systems without altering their data structures is usually known as VFAT (for "Virtual FAT") after the Windows 95 virtual device driver.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Non VFAT-enabled operating systems can still access the files under their short file name alias without restrictions; however, the associated long file names may be lost when files with long filenames are copied under non VFAT-aware operating systems.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In Windows NT, support for VFAT long filenames began with version 3.5.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Linux provides a VFAT filesystem driver to work with FAT volumes with VFAT long filenames.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] For some time, a UVFAT driver was available to provide combined support for UMSDOS-style permissions with VFAT long filenames.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] OS/2 added long filename support to FAT using extended attributes (EA) before the introduction of VFAT.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Thus, VFAT long filenames are invisible to OS/2, and EA long filenames are invisible to Windows; therefore, experienced users of both operating systems would have to manually rename the files.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Human68K supported up to 18.3 filenames and (Shift JIS) Kanji characters in a proprietary FAT file system variant.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In order to support Java applications, the FlexOS-based IBM 4690 OS version 2 introduced its own virtual file system (VFS) architecture to store long filenames in the FAT file system in a backwards-compatible fashion.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] If enabled, the virtual filenames (VFN) are available under separate logical drive letters, whereas the real filenames (RFN) remain available under the original drive letters.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The FAT file system itself is not designed for supporting alternate data streams (ADS), but some operating systems that heavily depend on them have devised various methods for handling them on FAT volumes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Such methods either store the additional information in extra files and directories (classic Mac OS and macOS), or give new semantics to previously unused fields of the FAT on-disk data structures (OS/2 and Windows NT).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Mac OS using PC Exchange stores its various dates, file attributes and long filenames in a hidden file called "`FINDER.DAT`", and resource forks (a common Mac OS ADS) in a subdirectory called "`RESOURCE.FRK`", in every directory where they are used.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] From PC Exchange 2.1 onwards, they store the Mac OS long filenames as standard FAT long filenames and convert FAT filenames longer than 31 characters to unique 31-character filenames, which can then be made visible to Macintosh applications.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Early Linux distributions also supported a format known as UMSDOS, a FAT variant with Unix file attributes (such as long file name and access permissions) stored in a separate file called "`--linux-.---`".
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] UMSDOS fell into disuse after VFAT was released and it is not enabled by default in Linux from version 2.5.7 onwards.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] For some time, Linux also provided combined support for UMSDOS-style permissions and VFAT long filenames through UVFAT.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Support for **FAT32+** and **FAT16+** is limited to some versions of DR-DOS and not available in mainstream operating systems.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In its NetWare File System (NWFS) Novell implemented a heavily modified variant of a FAT file system for the NetWare operating system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] For larger files it utilized a performance feature named Turbo FAT.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] FATX is a family of file systems designed for Microsoft's Xbox video game console hard disk drives and memory cards, introduced in 2001.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] While resembling the same basic design ideas as FAT16 and FAT32, the **FATX16** and **FATX32** on-disk structures are simplified, but fundamentally incompatible with normal FAT16 and FAT32 file systems, making it impossible for normal FAT file system drivers to mount such volumes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The non-bootable superblock sector is 4 KB in size and holds an 18 byte large BPB-like structure completely different from normal BPBs.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Clusters are typically 16 KB in size and there is only one copy of the FAT on the Xbox.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Directory entries are 64 bytes in size instead of the normal 32 bytes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Files can have filenames up to 42 characters long using the OEM character set and be up to 4 GB minus 1 byte in size.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The on-disk timestamps hold creation, modification and access dates and times but differ from FAT: in FAT, the epoch is 1980; in FATX, the epoch is 2000.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] exFAT is a file system introduced with Windows Embedded CE 6.0 in November 2006 and brought to the Windows NT family with Vista Service Pack 1 and Windows XP Service Pack 3 (or separate installation of Windows XP Update KB955704).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] It is loosely based on the File Allocation Table architecture, but incompatible and protected by patents.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] exFAT is intended for use on flash drives and memory cards such as SDXC and Memory Stick XC, where FAT32 is otherwise used.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Vendors usually pre-format SDXC cards with it.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Its main benefit is its exceeding of the 4 GB file size limit, as file size references are stored with eight instead of four bytes, increasing the limit to 264 − 1 bytes.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Microsoft's GUI and command-line format utilities offer it as an alternative to NTFS (and, for smaller partitions, to FAT16B and FAT32).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The MBR partition type is `0x07` (the same as used for IFS, HPFS, and NTFS).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Logical geometry information located in the VBR is stored in a format not resembling any kind of BPB.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In early 2010, the file system was reverse-engineered by the SANS Institute.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] On August 28, 2019, Microsoft published the technical specification for exFAT so that it can be used in the Linux kernel and other operating systems.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Microsoft applied for, and was granted, a series of patents for key parts of the FAT file system in the mid-1990s.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] On December 3, 2003, Microsoft announced that it would be offering licenses for use of its FAT specification and "associated intellectual property", at the cost of a US$0.25 royalty per unit sold, with a US$250,000 maximum royalty per license agreement.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] To this end, Microsoft cited four patents on the FAT file system as the basis of its intellectual property claims.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In the EFI FAT32 specification, Microsoft specifically grants a number of rights, which many readers have interpreted as permitting operating system vendors to implement FAT.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Non-Microsoft patents affecting FAT include: U.S. patent 5,367,671, specific to the OS/2 extended object attributes (expired in 2011).
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The Public Patent Foundation (PUBPAT) submitted evidence to the U.S.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) in 2004 disputing the validity of U.S. patent 5,579,517, including prior art references from Xerox and IBM.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The USPTO opened an investigation and concluded by rejecting all claims in the patent.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] The next year, the USPTO further announced that following the re-examination process, it affirmed the rejection of '517 and additionally found U.S. patent 5,758,352 invalid on the grounds that the patent had incorrect assignees.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] However, in 2006, the USPTO ruled that features of Microsoft's implementation of the FAT system were "novel and non-obvious", reversing both earlier decisions and leaving the patents valid.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In February 2009, Microsoft filed a patent infringement lawsuit against TomTom alleging that the device maker's products infringe on patents related to VFAT long filenames.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] As some TomTom products are based on Linux, this marked the first time that Microsoft tried to enforce its patents against the Linux platform.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In October 2010, Microsoft filed a patent infringement lawsuit against Motorola alleging several patents (including two of the VFAT patents) were not licensed for use in the Android operating system.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] They also submitted a complaint to the ITC.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] Developers of open source software have designed methods intended to circumvent Microsoft's patents.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] In 2013, patent EP0618540 "common name space for long and short filenames" (expired since 2014) was invalidated in Germany.
[src:ntfs-filesystem/file-allocation-table] After the appeal was withdrawn, this judgment became final on 28 October 2015.
